{{Infobox criminal |name = Ruth Brown Snyder |image_name = Ruth Brown Snyder.jpg |image_size = |image_alt = |image_caption = |nationality = |birth_name = Ruth Brown |birth_date = March 27, 1895 |birth_place = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], U.S. |death_date = {{Death date and age|1928|1|12|1895|3|27|mf=yes}} |death_place = [[Sing Sing Prison]], [[Ossining (town), New York|Ossining, New York]], U.S. |charge = [[Murder]] |conviction_status = Executed by [[electric chair]] |occupation = Housewife |spouse = Albert Snyder (died 1927) |children = 1 }} [[File:Ruth Brown Snyder mugshot.jpg|thumb|Mugshot for her transfer to Sing Sing Prison in 1927]] '''Ruth Brown Snyder''' (March 27, 1895 – January 12, 1928) was an American [[murderer]]. Her [[death penalty|execution]] in the [[electric chair]] at [[Sing Sing Prison]] for the murder of her husband, Albert, was recorded in a well-publicized photograph.
==Crime== In 1925, Snyder was a housewife from [[Queens Village, Queens]], [[New York City]] who began an affair with Henry Judd Gray, a married [[corset]] salesman. She then began to plan the murder of her husband, enlisting the help of her new lover, though he appeared to be very reluctant. Her distaste for her husband apparently began when he insisted on hanging a picture of his late [[fiancée]], Jessie Guischard, on the wall of their first home, and named his boat after her. Guischard, whom Albert described to Ruth as "the finest woman I have ever met," had been dead for ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:93NhH52erasJ:http://www.trivia-library.com/a/the-snyder-gray-murder-case-part-2.htm+Ruth+Brown+Snyder+was+born&hl=en&strip=1|title=Snyder/Gray case details|publisher=}}</ref>
Ruth Snyder first persuaded her husband to purchase insurance, and, with the assistance of an insurance agent (who was subsequently fired and sent to prison for [[forgery]]) "signed" a $48,000 [[life insurance]] policy that paid extra ("[[double indemnity]]") if an unexpected act of violence killed the victim. According to Henry Judd Gray, Ruth had made at least seven attempts to kill her husband, all of which he survived.<ref name=murder/><ref name=story>{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1928/01/13/page/2/article/ruths-brother-and-mother-object-to-prison-post-mortem|title=Story of the Crime|date=January 13, 1928|publisher=Chicago Tribune|page=2|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref> On March 20, 1927, the couple [[garrotte]]d Albert Snyder and stuffed his nose full of [[chloroform]]-soaked rags, then staged his death as part of a burglary.<ref name=story/> Detectives at the scene noted that the burglar left little evidence of breaking into the house. Moreover, the behavior of Mrs. Snyder was inconsistent with her story of a terrorized wife witnessing her husband being killed.<ref name=murder>{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1935/12/29/page/65/article/snyder-murder-husband-victim-of-wife-and-her-weakling-paramour|title=Snyder Murder|author=Murchie, Guy, Jr.|date=December 29, 1935|pages=9–10|publisher=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref>
The police then found the property that Ruth claimed had been stolen. It was still in the house, but hidden. A breakthrough came when a detective found a paper with the letters "J.G." on it (it was a memento Albert Snyder had kept from former lover Jessie Guischard), and asked Ruth about it. A flustered Ruth's mind immediately turned to her lover, whose initials were also "J.G.," and she asked the detective what Gray had to do with this. It was the first time Gray had been mentioned, and the police were instantly suspicious. Gray was found upstate, in [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]]. He claimed he had been there all night, but eventually it turned out a friend of his had created an alibi, setting up Gray's room at a hotel. Gray proved far more forthcoming than Ruth about his actions. He was caught and returned to [[Jamaica, New York|Jamaica, Queens]] and charged along with Ruth Snyder.<ref name=murder/><ref name=story/> [[Dorothy Parker]] told Oscar Levant, an American in Paris, that Gray tried to escape the police by taking a taxi from [[Long Island]] to Manhattan, New York, which Levant noted was "quite a long trip." According to Parker, in order "not to attract attention, he gave the driver a ten-cent tip."<ref>{{cite book|last=Levant|first=Oscar|title=The Memoirs of an Amnesiac|publisher=G. P. Putnam's Sons|year=1965|location=New York|page=90}}</ref>
===The trial=== Snyder was imprisoned at [[Sing Sing]] in [[Ossining (town), New York|Ossining, New York]], about 30 miles north of New York City. Her prison cell there would in the future also be used to hold Eva Coo and "Lonely Hearts killer" [[Raymond Fernandez and Martha Beck|Martha Beck]].{{citation needed|date = March 2018}}
The trial at the [[Long Island City]] Courthouse was covered by such figures as [[Peggy Hopkins Joyce]], [[Mary Roberts Rinehart]], [[Aimee Semple McPherson]], [[D. W. Griffith]], [[Damon Runyon]], [[Will Durant]], [[James M. Cain]] (crime reporter who wrote the novella that became the movie, ''[[Double Indemnity (film)|Double Indemnity]]'') and, a year before her own death from [[cancer]], [[Nora Bayes]].{{citation needed|date = March 2018}} Runyon disparaged the crime's status as a clever attempt at a murder—he nicknamed it "the dumb-bell murder case" because "it was so dumb!"{{citequote|date = March 2018}}
[[File:Snyder chair.jpg|thumb|Ruth Snyder's mid-execution photo taken by [[Tom Howard (photographer)|Tom Howard]] and published the next day in the ''New York Daily News''.]]
Ruth Snyder and Gray turned on each other, contending the other was responsible for killing Albert Snyder; both were convicted and [[death penalty|sentenced to death]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1927/05/05/page/1/article/women-faint-at-grays-horror-story|title=Women Faint at Gray's Horror Story|date=May 5, 1927|pages=2, 4|publisher=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref>
===Execution=== On January 12, 1928, Snyder became the first woman to be executed in Sing Sing since 1899. She went to the electric chair only moments before her former lover.<ref name=murder/><ref name=story/> Her execution (by [[New York State Electrician]] [[Robert G. Elliott]]) was caught on film, by a photograph of her as the electricity was running through her body, with the aid of a miniature plate camera custom-strapped to the ankle of [[Tom Howard (photographer)|Tom Howard]], a ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' photographer working in cooperation with the ''Tribune''-owned ''[[New York Daily News]]''.<ref name="siedu">{{cite web|url=http://historywired.si.edu/object.cfm?ID=472|title=HistoryWired: A Few of Our Favorite Things|website=National Museum of American History}}</ref> Howard's camera was owned for a while by inventor [[Miller Reese Hutchison]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Owner of camera that took death cell pictures a recent visitor here|url=http://bplonline.cdmhost.com/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/p4017coll2&CISOPTR=171&CISOBOX=1&REC=4|work=Clipping from [[The Birmingham News]]|publisher=[[Birmingham Public Library]]|date=February 9, 1938|accessdate=2010-04-20}}</ref> and later became part of the collections of the [[Smithsonian|Smithsonian's]] [[National Museum of American History]].<ref name="siedu"/>
Snyder was interred in the [[Woodlawn Cemetery (Bronx)|Woodlawn Cemetery]] in The [[The Bronx|Bronx]], New York City. Her gravestone simply reads "Brown".<ref>{{Find a Grave|963}}</ref>
==Lorraine Snyder== Albert and Ruth had one child, a daughter named Lorraine, who was nine at the time of her father's murder. Following the pronouncement of the death sentence on her mother in May 1927, legal disputes arose between the relatives of both Albert and Ruth Snyder regarding the care of Lorraine. Warren Schneider, <!-- no explanation of why variation of brothers' surname spelling -->brother of Albert Snyder, petitioned to be allowed to appoint a legal guardian who was not a member of Ruth Snyder's family. Josephine Brown, mother of Ruth Snyder, also petitioned for custody of the girl.<ref>{{cite news|title=To Seek Guardian for Lorraine Snyder|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Kq0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fGkFAAAAIBAJ&dq=lorraine+snyder&pg=4608,3431254|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Lewiston Daily Sun|date=May 12, 1927}}</ref> Lorraine had been in the care of Mrs. Brown since the murder.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ruth Snyder's Family|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=supPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3lQDAAAAIBAJ&dq=josephine+brown&pg=2323,5380779|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Evening Independent|date=January 10, 1928}}</ref> Lorraine was formally placed by her maternal grandmother in the Catholic institution where she had been residing at the time of her mother's execution. Ruth requested that her daughter not be brought to the prison for a final visit.<ref name="news.google.com">{{cite news|title=To Rush Snyder Insurance Case|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HcsaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4ksEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2713,738843|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=January 13, 1928}}</ref>
[[File:Ruth Snyder Brown Grave 1024.jpg|thumb|The grave of Ruth Brown Snyder in [[Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx|Woodlawn Cemetery]].]]On September 7, 1927, Josephine Brown was awarded guardianship of the girl.<ref name="news.google.com"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Give Snyder Tot to Grandparent|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WzkbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LUoEAAAAIBAJ&dq=custody+lorraine+snyder&pg=1006,2571474|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=September 7, 1927}}</ref> During this time, there were disputes with the insurance company Ruth Snyder had used to insure her husband's life. Although one policy, worth [[US$]]30,000, was paid out without contest,<ref>{{cite news|title=Dual Execution Makes Trio Ill|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HssaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4ksEAAAAIBAJ&dq=josephine+brown&pg=1978,1172947|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=January 14, 1928}}</ref> they filed suit to void two other policies, worth $45,000 and $5,000 (the three combined policies worth ${{Inflation|US|0.08|1927|r=2|fmt=c}} million today). By May 1928, the insurance company made available $4,000 for the maintenance of Lorraine. In November 1928 a ruling in the case was reached, with a court finding the policies could not be collected as they had been issued fraudulently.<ref>{{cite news|title=Appeal Ruling Against Child|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=328bAAAAIBAJ&sjid=80oEAAAAIBAJ&dq=lorraine+snyder&pg=6348,352384|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Pittsburgh Press|date=November 11, 1928}}</ref> At the time of the judgment, the lawyer acting on behalf of Snyder and Brown asked the court to allow them to appeal without a printed record, on the basis that the family was destitute and unable to sell the house due to the notoriety of the case. By May 1930 it was finally ruled on appeal that the two policies were invalid.<ref>{{cite news|title=Snyder Insurance Policies Not Valid|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SB0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lWYFAAAAIBAJ&dq=josephine+brown+snyder&pg=4876,7417631|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Lewiston Daily Sun|date=June 21, 1930}}</ref>
During her time on death row, Ruth Snyder wrote a sealed letter to be given to Lorraine "when she is old enough to understand".<ref>{{cite news|title=Girls, Orphaned Years Ago By Chair, Happy|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kOtXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=60QNAAAAIBAJ&dq=josephine+brown+lorraine+snyder&pg=6876,1263081|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=The Toledo News-Bee|date=January 12, 1929}}</ref> One year after her mother's execution, Lorraine was apparently aware that her parents were both dead, but not of the manner of either of their deaths.<ref>''Murder Casebook'' {{ISBN|0-748-51462-7}} p. 2212</ref>
==Depiction in popular media== * The drama ''[[Machinal]]'' (1928), by playwright Sophie Treadwell, is based on Snyder's trial. * The movies ''[[Blessed Event]]'' (1932) and ''[[Picture Snatcher]]'' (1933) make references to Snyder's execution. {{Citation needed|date=December 2010}} * A fictionalized version of the trial was the basis of scenes in ''[[State's Attorney (film)|State's Attorney]]'' (1932) with John Barrymore as the prosecutor. * The case was the inspiration for the novel ''[[Double Indemnity (novel)|Double Indemnity]]'' (1943) by [[James M. Cain]],<ref name="trutv">{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/cops_others/robert_elliott/6.html?print=yes|title=truTV Official Website - TV Show Full Episodes and Funny Video Clips|website=www.trutv.com}}</ref> which was later [[Double Indemnity (film)|adapted for the screen]] (1944) by [[Billy Wilder]] and [[Raymond Chandler]]. * Cain also mentioned that his book ''[[The Postman Always Rings Twice (novel)|The Postman Always Rings Twice]]'' (1934) took inspiration from the crime <ref name="The Art of Fiction">{{cite web|url=http://www.theparisreview.org/interviews/3474/the-art-of-fiction-no-69-james-m-cain|title=James M. Cain, The Art of Fiction No. 69|first=Interviewed by David|last=Zinsser|publisher=}}</ref> * Near the end of the 1951 film ''[[The Thing from Another World]]'', a reporter, Scotty, mentions that Snyder's execution was the first he ever covered. When another character asks Scotty if he was able to get a picture, Scotty answers, "No, they didn't allow cameras, but one guy . . . ." The approach of "The Thing" interrupts him, but Scotty is seemingly referring to Howard's photo of Snyder in the electric chair. * In ''[[The Bad Seed]]'', [[William March]] based his depiction of Bessie Denker's execution upon that of Ruth Snyder. * [[Guns N' Roses]]' 1991 ''[[Use Your Illusion]]'' albums feature, as part of their enclosed artwork, a photo of the band posing in front of an oversized reproduction of the ''Daily News''' headline/photograph announcing Ruth Snyder's execution. * The novel ''A Wild Surge of Guilty Passion'' (2011), by [[Ron Hansen (novelist)|Ron Hansen]], is based on the murder case. <!-- isbn neeeded -->{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}
